WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.740 --> 00:00:04.612
Professor Ben Polak: So
last time we finished up by

00:00:04.612 --> 00:00:06.930
playing the game of Nim and
you'll remember,

00:00:06.930 --> 00:00:11.135
I hope, that the game of Nim
was a game where there was two

00:00:11.135 --> 00:00:15.412
piles of stones--we made do with
lines on the board--and the

00:00:15.412 --> 00:00:19.400
winner was the person who picked
up the last stone.

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:23.528
Remember you had to pick piles.
I want to use the game of Nim

00:00:23.528 --> 00:00:27.347
to make a transition here.
So what we had pointed out

00:00:27.347 --> 00:00:31.112
about the game of Nim was it
illustrated very nicely for us

00:00:31.112 --> 00:00:34.877
that games can have first mover
advantages or they can have

00:00:34.877 --> 00:00:38.314
second mover advantages.
A very small change in the

00:00:38.314 --> 00:00:42.140
game, essentially a very small
change in where we started from,

00:00:42.140 --> 00:00:46.565
could switch a game from a game
with a first mover advantage to

00:00:46.565 --> 00:00:49.350
a game with a second mover
advantage.

00:00:49.350 --> 00:00:54.326
Now today, I want to just draw
a slightly grander lesson out of

00:00:54.326 --> 00:00:56.762
that game.
So not only was it the case

00:00:56.762 --> 00:00:59.653
that the game sometimes has
first mover advantages and

00:00:59.653 --> 00:01:01.890
sometimes has second mover
advantages,

00:01:01.890 --> 00:01:04.562
but moreover,
we could tell when it had a

00:01:04.562 --> 00:01:08.503
first mover advantage and we
could tell when it had a second

00:01:08.503 --> 00:01:10.349
mover advantage.
Is that right?

00:01:10.349 --> 00:01:13.446
When we actually looked at the
initial set up of those stones,

00:01:13.446 --> 00:01:16.441
we knew immediately that's a
game in which Player 1 is going

00:01:16.441 --> 00:01:18.171
to win,
or alternatively,

00:01:18.171 --> 00:01:22.237
we knew immediately that's a
game which Player 2 is going to

00:01:22.237 --> 00:01:24.733
win.
Now it turns out that that idea

00:01:24.733 --> 00:01:28.241
is very general and actually has
a name attached to it,

00:01:28.241 --> 00:01:30.060
and that name is Zermelo.

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:38.985
So today we'll start off by
talking about a theorem due to a

00:01:38.985 --> 00:01:42.057
guy called Zermelo,
and the idea of this theorem is

00:01:42.057 --> 00:01:44.003
this.
We're going to look at games

00:01:44.003 --> 00:01:46.642
more general than just Nim,
and we're going to ask the

00:01:46.642 --> 00:01:49.078
question,
under what circumstances would

00:01:49.078 --> 00:01:51.652
you know about a game either
that Player 1,

00:01:51.652 --> 00:01:54.661
the person who goes first,
can force a win,

00:01:54.661 --> 00:01:58.815
or that Player 2 can force a
win, or will allow a third

00:01:58.815 --> 00:02:03.530
possibility,
which is it's going to be a tie.

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:06.766
So here's the theorem,
suppose there are two players

00:02:06.766 --> 00:02:09.431
in this game,
like the games that we looked

00:02:09.431 --> 00:02:13.060
at last time,
and suppose--I won't define

00:02:13.060 --> 00:02:18.633
this formally now--but suppose
the game is a game of perfect

00:02:18.633 --> 00:02:21.245
information.
So what do I mean by perfect

00:02:21.245 --> 00:02:23.676
information?
I'll define this later on in

00:02:23.676 --> 00:02:27.631
the class, but for now all I
mean is, that whenever a player

00:02:27.631 --> 00:02:31.185
has his turn to move,
that player knows exactly what

00:02:31.185 --> 00:02:34.012
has happened prior in the game.
So, for example,

00:02:34.012 --> 00:02:36.927
all these sequential move games
we've been looking at are moves

00:02:36.927 --> 00:02:39.501
of perfect information.
When I get to move I know

00:02:39.501 --> 00:02:42.528
exactly what you did yesterday,
I know what I did the day

00:02:42.528 --> 00:02:45.459
before yesterday and so on.
So it's a game of perfect

00:02:45.459 --> 00:02:48.557
information.
I'm going to assume that the

00:02:48.557 --> 00:02:51.580
game has a finite number of
nodes.

00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:54.395
So two things here,
it can't go on forever,

00:02:54.395 --> 00:02:58.550
this game, and also there's no
point in which it branches in an

00:02:58.550 --> 00:03:01.490
infinite way.
So there's a finite number of

00:03:01.490 --> 00:03:04.905
nodes, and we'll assume that the
game has three possible

00:03:04.905 --> 00:03:07.073
outcomes.
Actually there's a more general

00:03:07.073 --> 00:03:09.370
version of this theorem but this
will do for now.

00:03:09.370 --> 00:03:14.224
The three possible outcomes are
either a win for Player 1,

00:03:14.224 --> 00:03:19.534
so I'll call it W_1,
or a loss for Player 1,

00:03:19.534 --> 00:03:25.039
which is obviously a win for
Player 2, or a tie.

00:03:25.039 --> 00:03:27.579
So the game--like Nim last
time, that only had two

00:03:27.579 --> 00:03:30.543
outcomes.
So here we're going to look up

00:03:30.543 --> 00:03:35.250
to three outcomes or three or
fewer outcomes I should say.

00:03:35.250 --> 00:03:39.930
So these are the conditions and
here's the result.

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:42.822
So I said three,
it could be three but it could

00:03:42.822 --> 00:03:45.840
also be two here,
I'm just allowing for three.

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:51.652
(One is trivial.) So under
these conditions the following

00:03:51.652 --> 00:03:55.303
is true.
Either Player 1 can force a

00:03:55.303 --> 00:04:01.111
win, so either it's the case
that this game is a game that if

00:04:01.111 --> 00:04:04.789
Player 1 plays as well as they
can,

00:04:04.789 --> 00:04:09.759
they're going to win the game
no matter what Player 2 does.

00:04:09.759 --> 00:04:17.089
Or 1 can at least force a tie,
which means Player 1 can play

00:04:17.089 --> 00:04:23.673
in such a way that they can
assure themselves of a tie

00:04:23.673 --> 00:04:28.269
regardless of what Player 2
does.

00:04:28.269 --> 00:04:41.222
Or it could be a game in which
2 can force a loss on 1,

00:04:41.222 --> 00:04:45.977
so a win for 2.
So this theorem,

00:04:45.977 --> 00:04:48.221
when you first look at it,
it doesn't seem to say very

00:04:48.221 --> 00:04:49.848
much.
You're staring at this

00:04:49.848 --> 00:04:52.719
thing--you might think,
we already knew that we're

00:04:52.719 --> 00:04:56.410
looking at games that only have
three possible outcomes win,

00:04:56.410 --> 00:05:00.440
loss, or tie so it doesn't seem
so surprising if you look at

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:02.079
this theorem,
it says,

00:05:02.079 --> 00:05:04.563
well, you're going to end up
with a win, or a loss,

00:05:04.563 --> 00:05:06.522
or a tie.
However, that's not quite what

00:05:06.522 --> 00:05:08.356
the theorem says.
The theorem says,

00:05:08.356 --> 00:05:11.316
not only are you going to end
up there--we knew that

00:05:11.316 --> 00:05:13.870
already--but the games divide
themselves.

00:05:13.870 --> 00:05:17.200
Games of these forms divide
themselves into those games in

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:20.298
which Player 1 has a way of
winning regardless of what

00:05:20.298 --> 00:05:23.612
Player 2 does;
or games in which Player 1 has

00:05:23.612 --> 00:05:27.306
a way of forcing a tie
regardless of what Player 2

00:05:27.306 --> 00:05:29.528
does;
or Player 2 has a way of

00:05:29.528 --> 00:05:32.226
winning regardless of what
Player 1 does,

00:05:32.226 --> 00:05:34.790
so these games all have a
solution.

00:05:34.790 --> 00:05:37.990
Let's just go back to Nim to
illustrate the point.

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:41.749
So in Nim actually there's no
tie so we can forget the middle

00:05:41.749 --> 00:05:45.433
of these, and in Nim,
under certain circumstances it

00:05:45.433 --> 00:05:48.649
is the case that Player 1 can
force a win.

00:05:48.649 --> 00:05:52.137
Who remembers what the case
was, for when Player 1 can force

00:05:52.137 --> 00:05:54.450
a win?
Anybody?

00:05:54.450 --> 00:06:00.260
The people who played last time.
No, yes, Ale,

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:04.500
there's somebody here.
Shout it out.

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:06.810
Student: Insuring that
the piles are equal for the

00:06:06.810 --> 00:06:10.040
other player.
Professor Ben Polak: All

00:06:10.040 --> 00:06:14.588
right, so if the piles start
unequal, then Player 1 can

00:06:14.588 --> 00:06:21.232
actually force a win.
So in Nim if the piles are

00:06:21.232 --> 00:06:29.410
unequal at the start,
then 1 can force a win.

00:06:29.410 --> 00:06:33.819
It really doesn't matter what 2
does, 2 is "toast."

00:06:33.819 --> 00:06:37.982
Or the alternative case is the
piles are equal at the start,

00:06:37.982 --> 00:06:42.003
and if they're equal at the
start then it's Player 1 who's

00:06:42.003 --> 00:06:44.764
"toast."
Player 2 is going

00:06:44.764 --> 00:06:51.181
to--rather--force a loss on 1,
so 2 can force a loss on 1,

00:06:51.181 --> 00:06:55.050
i.e.
a win for Player 2.

00:06:55.050 --> 00:06:58.940
Does everyone remember that
from last time?

00:06:58.940 --> 00:07:02.649
It's just before the weekend,
it shouldn't be so long ago.

00:07:02.649 --> 00:07:08.450
So this theorem applies to all
games of this form.

00:07:08.450 --> 00:07:10.862
So what games are of this form?
Let's try and think of some

00:07:10.862 --> 00:07:15.199
other examples.
So one example is tic-tac-toe.

00:07:15.199 --> 00:07:16.279
Everyone know the rules of
tic-tac-toe?

00:07:16.279 --> 00:07:18.840
In England we call it Noughts
and Crosses, but you guys call

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:20.230
it tic-tac-toe,
is that right?

00:07:20.230 --> 00:07:22.149
Everyone know what tic-tac-toe
is?

00:07:22.149 --> 00:07:26.389
Yeah, which category is
tic-tac-toe?

00:07:26.389 --> 00:07:29.897
Is it a game which Player 1 can
force a win, or is it a category

00:07:29.897 --> 00:07:32.180
in which Player 1 can only force
a tie,

00:07:32.180 --> 00:07:35.169
or is it a category which you'd
rather go second and Player 2

00:07:35.169 --> 00:07:37.860
can force a win for Player 2 or
a loss for Player 1?

00:07:37.860 --> 00:07:41.759
Which is tic-tac-toe?
Let's have a show of hands here.

00:07:41.759 --> 00:07:45.581
Who thinks tic-tac-toe is a
game in which Player 1 can force

00:07:45.581 --> 00:07:47.644
a win?
Who thinks tic-tac-toe is a

00:07:47.644 --> 00:07:50.220
game in which Player 1 can only
force a tie?

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:53.690
Who thinks Player 2's going to
win?

00:07:53.690 --> 00:07:56.376
Most of you are right.
It's a game in which if people

00:07:56.376 --> 00:07:59.139
play correctly then it'll turn
out to be a tie.

00:07:59.139 --> 00:08:07.939
So tic-tac-toe is a game that
leads to a tie.

00:08:07.939 --> 00:08:10.917
Player 1 can still make a
mistake, in which case they can

00:08:10.917 --> 00:08:13.294
lose.
Player 2 can make a mistake in

00:08:13.294 --> 00:08:17.036
which case they would lose,
but there is a way of playing

00:08:17.036 --> 00:08:19.662
that forces a tie.
So these are fairly simple

00:08:19.662 --> 00:08:21.920
games, let's talk about more
complicated games.

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:24.839
So what about the game of
checkers?

00:08:24.839 --> 00:08:26.470
So the game of checkers meets
these conditions.

00:08:26.470 --> 00:08:29.686
It's a two player game.
You always know all the moves

00:08:29.686 --> 00:08:31.555
prior to your move.
It's finite:

00:08:31.555 --> 00:08:34.641
there's some rules in checkers
that prevent it going on

00:08:34.641 --> 00:08:36.499
forever.
And there are two or three

00:08:36.499 --> 00:08:39.242
outcomes: I guess there's a
third outcome if you get into a

00:08:39.242 --> 00:08:42.043
cycle you could tie.
So checkers fits all these

00:08:42.043 --> 00:08:45.340
descriptions and what this
theorem tells us is that

00:08:45.340 --> 00:08:48.234
checkers has a solution.
I'm not sure I know what that

00:08:48.234 --> 00:08:50.578
solution is, or I think actually
somebody did compute it quite

00:08:50.578 --> 00:08:52.065
recently,
even in the last few months,

00:08:52.065 --> 00:08:54.190
I just forgot to Google it this
morning to remind myself.

00:08:54.190 --> 00:08:57.808
But what this theorem tells us
even before those people that

00:08:57.808 --> 00:09:00.200
computed it: checkers has a
solution.

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:04.270
Let's be a bit more ambitious.
What about chess?

00:09:04.270 --> 00:09:07.792
So chess meets this description.
Chess is a two player game,

00:09:07.792 --> 00:09:11.129
everybody knows all the moves
before them, it's sequential,

00:09:11.129 --> 00:09:15.103
it has finite number of moves,
it's a very large number but it

00:09:15.103 --> 00:09:18.230
is finite, and it has three
possible outcomes,

00:09:18.230 --> 00:09:21.821
a win, a loss, or a tie.
So let's be careful,

00:09:21.821 --> 00:09:25.275
the reason it's finite is that
if you cycle--I forget what it

00:09:25.275 --> 00:09:28.038
is--three times then the game is
declared a draw,

00:09:28.038 --> 00:09:30.478
declared a tie.
So what's this theorem telling

00:09:30.478 --> 00:09:35.524
us?
It's telling us that there is a

00:09:35.524 --> 00:09:41.700
way to solve chess.
Chess has a solution.

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:43.100
We don't know what that
solution is.

00:09:43.100 --> 00:09:45.853
It could be that solution is
that Player 1,

00:09:45.853 --> 00:09:49.590
who's the player with the white
pieces can force a win.

00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:52.080
It could be that Player 1 can
only force a tie,

00:09:52.080 --> 00:09:54.950
and it could even be that
Player 2 can force a win.

00:09:54.950 --> 00:09:59.000
We don't know which it is,
but there is a solution.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.409
There's a catch to this theorem.
What's the catch?

00:10:02.409 --> 00:10:05.259
The catch is it doesn't
actually tell us--this theorem

00:10:05.259 --> 00:10:07.840
is not going to tell us what
that solution is.

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:10.111
It doesn't tell us how to play.
This theorem,

00:10:10.111 --> 00:10:12.484
in and of itself,
doesn't tell us how to play

00:10:12.484 --> 00:10:16.061
chess.
It just says there is a

00:10:16.061 --> 00:10:19.276
way to play chess.
So we're going to try and prove

00:10:19.276 --> 00:10:21.288
this.
We don't often do proofs in

00:10:21.288 --> 00:10:25.153
class, but the reason I want to
prove this particular one is

00:10:25.153 --> 00:10:28.952
because I think the proof is
instructive as part of sort of

00:10:28.952 --> 00:10:31.699
QR at Yale.
So here's another example here,

00:10:31.699 --> 00:10:34.770
and some other examples.
You could think of chess as

00:10:34.770 --> 00:10:36.850
being the most dramatic example.

00:10:49.019 --> 00:10:56.203
So the reason I want to spend
actually some time proving this

00:10:56.203 --> 00:11:03.388
today is because we're going to
prove it by induction and I'm

00:11:03.388 --> 00:11:08.213
going to sketch the proof.
I'm not going to go through

00:11:08.213 --> 00:11:10.909
every possible step but I want
to give people here a feeling

00:11:10.909 --> 00:11:12.919
for what a proof by induction
looks like.

00:11:12.919 --> 00:11:14.710
The reason for this is,
my guess is,

00:11:14.710 --> 00:11:17.115
well let's find out,
how many of you have seen a

00:11:17.115 --> 00:11:20.610
proof by induction before?
How many have not?

00:11:20.610 --> 00:11:22.633
So for those of you who haven't
I think it's a good thing in

00:11:22.633 --> 00:11:24.759
life, at one point in your life
to see a proof by induction,

00:11:24.759 --> 00:11:27.557
and for those who have,
my guess is you saw it in some

00:11:27.557 --> 00:11:30.883
awful math class in high school
and it just went over--it didn't

00:11:30.883 --> 00:11:32.889
necessarily go over your head
but,

00:11:32.889 --> 00:11:36.070
the excitement of it doesn't
catch on.

00:11:36.070 --> 00:11:40.140
This is a context where it
might appeal.

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:46.400
So proof by induction.
We're going to prove this by

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:57.384
induction on the maximum length
of the game and we'll call that

00:11:57.384 --> 00:11:59.291
N.
We'll call N the maximum length

00:11:59.291 --> 00:12:00.830
of the game.
What do I mean by this?

00:12:00.830 --> 00:12:06.001
If I write down a tree I can
always look at all the paths

00:12:06.001 --> 00:12:11.542
from the beginning of the tree
all the way through to the end

00:12:11.542 --> 00:12:14.719
of the tree.
And I'm going to look at the

00:12:14.719 --> 00:12:18.240
path in that particular tree
that has the largest length,

00:12:18.240 --> 00:12:21.742
and I'll call that the length
of the game, the maximum length

00:12:21.742 --> 00:12:24.586
of the game.
So we're going to do induction

00:12:24.586 --> 00:12:26.950
on the maximum length of the
game.

00:12:26.950 --> 00:12:28.710
So how do we start a proof by
induction?

00:12:28.710 --> 00:12:30.965
Let's just remind ourselves,
those people who have seen them

00:12:30.965 --> 00:12:33.572
before.
We're going to prove that this

00:12:33.572 --> 00:12:36.965
theorem this true,
the claim in the theorem is

00:12:36.965 --> 00:12:41.490
true for the easy case when the
game is only 1 move long.

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:45.524
That's the first step,
and then we're going to try and

00:12:45.524 --> 00:12:49.330
show that if it's true for all
games of length &lt;

00:12:49.330 --> 00:12:51.264
= N,
whatever N is,

00:12:51.264 --> 00:12:56.559
then it must therefore be true
for games of length N+1.

00:12:56.559 --> 00:12:58.850
That's the way you do a proof
by induction.

00:12:58.850 --> 00:13:01.750
So let's just see how that
works in practice.

00:13:01.750 --> 00:13:04.811
So let's start with the easy
step and we'll do it in some

00:13:04.811 --> 00:13:08.200
detail, more detail than you
really need to in a math class.

00:13:08.200 --> 00:13:11.250
So if N = 1,
what do these games look like?

00:13:11.250 --> 00:13:13.210
Well let's look at some
examples here.

00:13:13.210 --> 00:13:18.259
So I claim it's pretty trivial
if N = 1 but let's do it anyway.

00:13:18.259 --> 00:13:20.600
So the game might look like
this.

00:13:20.600 --> 00:13:22.912
Player 1 is going to
move--here's Player 1

00:13:22.912 --> 00:13:26.128
moving--the game's only length
one--so Player 1's the only

00:13:26.128 --> 00:13:30.059
player who ever gets to move.
So the game might look like

00:13:30.059 --> 00:13:31.999
this.
Let's put in a fifth branch,

00:13:31.999 --> 00:13:34.606
it might look like this.
And at the end of this game,

00:13:34.606 --> 00:13:37.269
rather than putting payoffs let
me just put the outcomes.

00:13:37.269 --> 00:13:40.215
So the outcome must either be a
win, or a tie,

00:13:40.215 --> 00:13:43.029
or a loss, so suppose it looks
like this.

00:13:43.029 --> 00:13:47.697
Suppose it's a win,
or here we could have a tie,

00:13:47.697 --> 00:13:53.357
or here we could have a win
again, or here we could have a

00:13:53.357 --> 00:13:57.230
loss, and here we could have a
tie.

00:13:57.230 --> 00:14:02.090
So in this particular game I
claim it's pretty clear this

00:14:02.090 --> 00:14:06.869
game has a solution.
It's pretty clear what 1 should

00:14:06.869 --> 00:14:08.129
do.
What should 1 do?

00:14:08.129 --> 00:14:12.360
1 should pick one of her
choices that leads to a win.

00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:15.582
To be careful I'll put 1 in
here just to distinguish who it

00:14:15.582 --> 00:14:17.750
is who's actually winning and
losing.

00:14:17.750 --> 00:14:21.149
So in this game I claim that
this game has a pretty obvious

00:14:21.149 --> 00:14:24.665
solution, either Player 1 is
going to choose this branch that

00:14:24.665 --> 00:14:27.830
leads to a win or this branch
that leads to a win,

00:14:27.830 --> 00:14:31.680
and either way Player 1 is
going to win.

00:14:31.680 --> 00:14:33.086
Is that obvious?
It's so obvious,

00:14:33.086 --> 00:14:35.548
it's kind of painful.
So I claim this game,

00:14:35.548 --> 00:14:39.960
we could actually replace this
first node with what's going to

00:14:39.960 --> 00:14:43.070
happen which is Player 1's going
to win.

00:14:43.070 --> 00:14:45.559
Is that right?
That was easy.

00:14:45.559 --> 00:14:49.740
Let's look at a different
example, we'll do three.

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:53.588
So here's another possible
example, and this again,

00:14:53.588 --> 00:14:57.899
Player 1 is going to move here
and this time the possible

00:14:57.899 --> 00:15:01.210
outcomes are tie,
or a loss, or a loss.

00:15:01.210 --> 00:15:05.272
Once again it's a one player
game, this time he has three

00:15:05.272 --> 00:15:09.480
choices and the three choices
lead to a tie or he loses,

00:15:09.480 --> 00:15:11.110
so I claim once again this is
simple.

00:15:11.110 --> 00:15:13.914
What Player 1 should do is what?
Choose the tie since there's no

00:15:13.914 --> 00:15:15.612
way of winning.
But in that case he could

00:15:15.612 --> 00:15:17.548
actually force it.
He could actually choose the

00:15:17.548 --> 00:15:19.330
tie in which case he's going to
tie.

00:15:19.330 --> 00:15:21.820
So this game has a solution
called choose the tie.

00:15:21.820 --> 00:15:25.717
And again, we could replace the
first node of the game with

00:15:25.717 --> 00:15:29.010
what's actually going to happen
which is a tie.

00:15:29.010 --> 00:15:32.523
Everyone happy?
There's one other possibility I

00:15:32.523 --> 00:15:35.086
guess.
The other possibility is that

00:15:35.086 --> 00:15:39.155
here Player 1 has a lot of
choices, maybe four choices in

00:15:39.155 --> 00:15:43.481
this case,
once again Player 1 is going to

00:15:43.481 --> 00:15:48.499
move but in each
case--unfortunately for Player

00:15:48.499 --> 00:15:54.389
1--in each case the outcome is
that Player 1 loses.

00:15:54.389 --> 00:15:56.798
So this is a game in which
Player 1 is going to lose no

00:15:56.798 --> 00:15:59.015
matter what they do.
Once again it has a solution:

00:15:59.015 --> 00:16:01.400
the solution is Player 1 is
toast and is going to lose.

00:16:08.129 --> 00:16:10.915
So I claim this has really
captured all the possibilities

00:16:10.915 --> 00:16:13.431
of games of length 1.
I mean you could imagine that

00:16:13.431 --> 00:16:16.268
there could be more branches on
them, but basically there are

00:16:16.268 --> 00:16:19.312
these three possibilities.
Either it's the case that one

00:16:19.312 --> 00:16:22.716
of those branches leads to a
win, in which case the solution

00:16:22.716 --> 00:16:25.485
is Player 1 wins;
or it's the case that none of

00:16:25.485 --> 00:16:28.659
the branches have wins in them,
but one of them has a tie,

00:16:28.659 --> 00:16:30.720
in which Player 1 is going to
tie;

00:16:30.720 --> 00:16:33.629
or it's the case that all the
branches have loss in them,

00:16:33.629 --> 00:16:35.500
in which Player 1's going to
lose.

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:38.350
So I claim I'm for done for
games of length one.

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:42.053
Everyone okay?
So that step is deceptively

00:16:42.053 --> 00:16:45.824
easy but there it is.
All right, now we do the

00:16:45.824 --> 00:16:47.529
inductive step,
the big step.

00:16:47.529 --> 00:16:50.494
What we're going to do is we're
going to assume that the

00:16:50.494 --> 00:16:53.452
statement of the theorem,
which I've now hidden

00:16:53.452 --> 00:16:57.817
unfortunately--let me unhide it
if I can, it's not going to be

00:16:57.817 --> 00:16:58.390
easy.

00:17:05.120 --> 00:17:10.692
This now visible?
So now let's assume that the

00:17:10.692 --> 00:17:17.638
statement of this theorem is
true for all games length &lt;

00:17:17.638 --> 00:17:29.058
= N, suppose that's the case.
Suppose the claim is true for

00:17:29.058 --> 00:17:41.619
all games of this type,
of length &lt;= some N.

00:17:41.619 --> 00:17:45.916
What we need to show is--what
we're going to try and show is

00:17:45.916 --> 00:17:50.140
therefore it will be true for
all games of length N + 1.

00:17:50.140 --> 00:17:58.984
What we want to show is--we
claim, therefore,

00:17:58.984 --> 00:18:07.225
it will be true for games of
length N + 1,

00:18:07.225 --> 00:18:16.069
that's the key step in
inductive proofs.

00:18:16.069 --> 00:18:19.589
All right, so how are we going
to do that?

00:18:19.589 --> 00:18:22.038
Well let's have a look at a
game of length N + 1,

00:18:22.038 --> 00:18:24.895
and obviously I can't use
thousands here so let me choose

00:18:24.895 --> 00:18:28.830
from relatively small numbers,
but the idea will go through.

00:18:28.830 --> 00:18:34.778
So let's have a look at a game.
So here's a game in which

00:18:34.778 --> 00:18:40.049
Player 1 moves first,
Player 2 moves second.

00:18:40.049 --> 00:18:44.522
Let's suppose that if Player 2
does this, then 1 only has

00:18:44.522 --> 00:18:48.814
little choice here,
up here then one has a more

00:18:48.814 --> 00:18:53.849
complicated choice,
and perhaps 2 could move again.

00:18:53.849 --> 00:18:55.872
So this is quite a complicated
little game up here,

00:18:55.872 --> 00:18:58.299
and down here let's make it a
little bit less complicated.

00:18:58.299 --> 00:19:02.504
Here the game looks like this
and then comes to an end,

00:19:02.504 --> 00:19:06.061
so the tree looks like this.
I haven't put the end,

00:19:06.061 --> 00:19:09.559
I haven't put the outcomes on
it but the tree looks like this.

00:19:09.559 --> 00:19:12.279
So how long is this tree first
of all?

00:19:12.279 --> 00:19:16.380
Well I claim that the longest
path in this tree,

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:20.480
from the beginning to the end
has four steps.

00:19:20.480 --> 00:19:23.410
Let's just check.
So one, two,

00:19:23.410 --> 00:19:27.650
three, four that's what I claim
is the longest path.

00:19:27.650 --> 00:19:33.107
Any path going down this way
only has three moves in it,

00:19:33.107 --> 00:19:36.579
so this is a game of length
four.

00:19:36.579 --> 00:19:42.061
So we can apply it to our
claim, let's assume that the

00:19:42.061 --> 00:19:47.440
theorem holds for all trees
length three or fewer,

00:19:47.440 --> 00:19:51.589
so that N + 1 is 4 for the
purpose of our example.

00:19:51.589 --> 00:19:57.937
So in this example--I don't
want to put it here,

00:19:57.937 --> 00:20:03.338
let's put it here--in this
example N = 3,

00:20:03.338 --> 00:20:09.704
so that N + 1 = 4.
Everyone happy with this in the

00:20:09.704 --> 00:20:12.948
example?
Now what I want to observe

00:20:12.948 --> 00:20:17.466
about this is the following:
contained in this N + 1,

00:20:17.466 --> 00:20:21.809
or the game of length 4 are
some smaller games.

00:20:21.809 --> 00:20:23.599
You could think of them as
sub-games.

00:20:23.599 --> 00:20:26.830
They're games within the game,
is that right?

00:20:26.830 --> 00:20:31.809
So let's have a look.
I claim, in particular--draw

00:20:31.809 --> 00:20:40.022
around them in pink--there's a
game here that follows Player 1

00:20:40.022 --> 00:20:47.561
choosing Up and there's a game
here that follows Player 1

00:20:47.561 --> 00:20:53.410
choosing Down,
is that right?

00:20:53.410 --> 00:20:58.640
Okay, so these are both games,
and what do we have here?

00:20:58.640 --> 00:21:02.134
So this little game in
here--the game in the top

00:21:02.134 --> 00:21:06.373
circle, the game that follows
Player 1 moving up--that's a

00:21:06.373 --> 00:21:10.574
game and it has a length.
So this little thing is a game

00:21:10.574 --> 00:21:14.527
and I'm going to call it a
sub-game, some jargon that we'll

00:21:14.527 --> 00:21:17.730
be getting used to later on in
the semester.

00:21:17.730 --> 00:21:25.340
It's a game within the game,
but it's basically just a game:

00:21:25.340 --> 00:21:32.823
it's a sub-game and this is a
sub-game following 1 choosing

00:21:32.823 --> 00:21:38.369
Up--let's put Up in
here--following up.

00:21:38.369 --> 00:21:41.814
And I claim that this game has
a length--this sub-game has a

00:21:41.814 --> 00:21:44.015
length.
So we knew that we started from

00:21:44.015 --> 00:21:46.610
a game of length 4,
we've taken one of the moves,

00:21:46.610 --> 00:21:50.069
and let's just make sure this
is actually a game of length 3.

00:21:50.069 --> 00:21:53.304
So the game started here,
this would be a game of length

00:21:53.304 --> 00:21:55.891
3 because you could go one,
two, three moves,

00:21:55.891 --> 00:21:59.009
is that right?
So this is a game of length 3.

00:21:59.009 --> 00:22:08.081
So this is a sub-game following
1 choosing Up and it,

00:22:08.081 --> 00:22:13.140
the sub-game,
has length 3.

00:22:13.140 --> 00:22:21.004
Down here, this is also a
sub-game, it's a game that

00:22:21.004 --> 00:22:29.948
follows Player 1 choosing Down
and this little sub-game has

00:22:29.948 --> 00:22:39.355
length--now here we have to be a
little bit careful--you might

00:22:39.355 --> 00:22:48.299
think that since we started from
a game of length 4,

00:22:48.299 --> 00:22:53.210
after the first move we must be
in a game of length 3.

00:22:53.210 --> 00:22:56.021
But actually that's not true,
and if we look carefully,

00:22:56.021 --> 00:22:58.885
we'll notice that this game
down here, the game starting

00:22:58.885 --> 00:23:02.410
here actually isn't of length 3.
It's of length 2.

00:23:02.410 --> 00:23:04.451
Is that right?
So even though started from a

00:23:04.451 --> 00:23:06.716
game of length 4,
by going this way we put

00:23:06.716 --> 00:23:08.760
ourselves into a game of length
2.

00:23:08.760 --> 00:23:16.023
Is that right?
So 1,2 or 1,2--whatever--it has

00:23:16.023 --> 00:23:20.708
length 2.
Okay, all right so in this

00:23:20.708 --> 00:23:25.868
example N is 3 and N + 1 is 4,
and our assumption,

00:23:25.868 --> 00:23:29.660
our induction assumption is
what?

00:23:29.660 --> 00:23:38.357
We've assumed that the claim of
the theorem holds for all games

00:23:38.357 --> 00:23:44.530
&lt;= N, which in this case
means &lt;= 3.

00:23:44.530 --> 00:23:47.396
So what does that tell us?
That tells us,

00:23:47.396 --> 00:23:51.593
by our assumption,
this game, which I've put a

00:23:51.593 --> 00:23:56.911
pink circle around on the top,
this is a game of length 3,

00:23:56.911 --> 00:24:02.315
this game has a solution.
It must have a solution because

00:24:02.315 --> 00:24:07.773
it's of length 3 or less.
So by the induction hypothesis

00:24:07.773 --> 00:24:14.649
as it's called--by the induction
hypothesis--this is a technical

00:24:14.649 --> 00:24:19.560
term, but what's the induction
hypothesis?

00:24:19.560 --> 00:24:29.687
It's this thing.
By the assumption that we made

00:24:29.687 --> 00:24:38.248
this game has a solution.
So it's a game of length 3,3

00:24:38.248 --> 00:24:40.819
&lt;= N in this case.
So this game must have a

00:24:40.819 --> 00:24:44.542
solution.
Now I don't immediately know by

00:24:44.542 --> 00:24:50.031
staring at it what it is,
but let's suppose it was W,

00:24:50.031 --> 00:24:53.589
say it was W.
And the game down below,

00:24:53.589 --> 00:24:57.562
this is also a game,
and it's a game of length 2 but

00:24:57.562 --> 00:25:00.599
2 is less than 3 as well,
2 &lt;= 3.

00:25:00.599 --> 00:25:06.289
So this game also has a
solution.

00:25:06.289 --> 00:25:13.717
This game also,
by the same assumption,

00:25:13.717 --> 00:25:22.709
has a solution,
so its solution is say--I don't

00:25:22.709 --> 00:25:29.009
know--maybe its L.
So what does that mean to say

00:25:29.009 --> 00:25:33.076
that these games have solutions,
in this case we're going to

00:25:33.076 --> 00:25:35.764
assume W is this one,
and L is this one,

00:25:35.764 --> 00:25:38.230
what does it mean?
It means that,

00:25:38.230 --> 00:25:41.690
just as we did with the games
up there, we could put the

00:25:41.690 --> 00:25:44.269
solution at the beginning of the
game.

00:25:44.269 --> 00:25:47.776
We know that if we get into
this game, we're going to get

00:25:47.776 --> 00:25:51.236
the solution of this game;
and we know if we get into this

00:25:51.236 --> 00:25:54.099
game, we're going to get the
solution of this game.

00:25:54.099 --> 00:25:58.837
So we can replace this one with
its solution which by assumption

00:25:58.837 --> 00:26:03.198
was W, and this one by its
solution which by assumption was

00:26:03.198 --> 00:26:04.977
L.
And here I want to be really

00:26:04.977 --> 00:26:08.011
careful, I need to keep track of
which person it is it's a win or

00:26:08.011 --> 00:26:10.820
loss for.
So this was a win for Player 1,

00:26:10.820 --> 00:26:14.867
hence it was a loss for Player
2, and this was a loss for

00:26:14.867 --> 00:26:18.119
Player 1, hence it was a win for
Player 2.

00:26:18.119 --> 00:26:22.063
So these games,
each of them have some

00:26:22.063 --> 00:26:28.350
solution, and this case I've
written down the solutions as W

00:26:28.350 --> 00:26:31.150
or L.
So now what could we do?

00:26:31.150 --> 00:26:33.349
Let me just bring down this
board again.

00:26:33.349 --> 00:26:37.329
I can translate this game into
a very simple game.

00:26:37.329 --> 00:26:40.929
I'm going to translate it up
here, so this game can be

00:26:40.929 --> 00:26:47.126
translated as follows.
Player 1 moves,

00:26:47.126 --> 00:27:06.609
if he goes Up then he hits a W
and if he goes Down he hits a L.

00:27:06.609 --> 00:27:09.958
So in this particular example,
Player 1 is effectively

00:27:09.958 --> 00:27:13.749
choosing between going Up and
finding himself in a game which

00:27:13.749 --> 00:27:16.797
has a solution,
and the solution is he wins it,

00:27:16.797 --> 00:27:20.014
or going Down and finding
himself in a game which has a

00:27:20.014 --> 00:27:24.640
solution,
and the solution is he's toast.

00:27:24.640 --> 00:27:29.329
But that's what?
That's a one move game.

00:27:29.329 --> 00:27:31.936
So we know this has a solution,
and in particular,

00:27:31.936 --> 00:27:37.259
he's going to choose Up.
This one has a solution.

00:27:37.259 --> 00:27:55.820
This has a solution,
it is a game of length 1.

00:27:55.820 --> 00:27:59.779
So what do we do?
Somewhat schematically,

00:27:59.779 --> 00:28:04.289
we took a game of length N + 1,
in this case that was 4;

00:28:04.289 --> 00:28:09.406
and we pointed out that once
Player 1 has made her first move

00:28:09.406 --> 00:28:12.220
in this game,
we are in a game,

00:28:12.220 --> 00:28:15.458
or in a sub-game if you like,
that has length less than 4,

00:28:15.458 --> 00:28:17.220
it could be 3,
it could be 2,

00:28:17.220 --> 00:28:21.894
whatever.
Whatever sub-game we're in,

00:28:21.894 --> 00:28:26.259
by assumption,
that game has a solution.

00:28:26.259 --> 00:28:29.542
So it's really effectively,
Player 1 is choosing between

00:28:29.542 --> 00:28:33.004
going into a game with solution
W or going into a game with

00:28:33.004 --> 00:28:35.351
solution L.
And if there were 15 other

00:28:35.351 --> 00:28:37.918
sub-games here,
each one would have a solution,

00:28:37.918 --> 00:28:41.322
and each one Player 1 would be
able to associate that solution

00:28:41.322 --> 00:28:44.559
with what he's going to
get--what she's going to get.

00:28:44.559 --> 00:28:49.647
So I claim that,
if it in fact is true that each

00:28:49.647 --> 00:28:55.710
of these sub-games of length 3
or less had a solution,

00:28:55.710 --> 00:28:59.293
then the game of length 4 must
have a solution,

00:28:59.293 --> 00:29:03.518
which is what?
It's the solution which is:

00:29:03.518 --> 00:29:07.930
Player 1 should pick the best
sub-game.

00:29:07.930 --> 00:29:11.299
Are people convinced by that
step?

00:29:11.299 --> 00:29:15.447
People are looking slightly
"deer in the headlamps" now,

00:29:15.447 --> 00:29:20.304
so let me just say it again.
We started by assuming that all

00:29:20.304 --> 00:29:23.569
games of length 3 or less,
or N or less,

00:29:23.569 --> 00:29:27.615
have a solution.
We pointed out that any game

00:29:27.615 --> 00:29:32.877
that has length N + 1 can be
thought of as an initial move by

00:29:32.877 --> 00:29:37.350
Player 1 followed by a game of
length N or less,

00:29:37.350 --> 00:29:41.287
N or fewer I should say.
Each of those games of N or

00:29:41.287 --> 00:29:45.418
fewer steps has a solution,
so Player 1 is just going to

00:29:45.418 --> 00:29:49.849
choose the game that has the
best solution for her and we're

00:29:49.849 --> 00:29:54.300
done.
In this particular example,

00:29:54.300 --> 00:30:02.388
Player 1 is going to choose Up
and therefore the solution to

00:30:02.388 --> 00:30:07.460
this parent game is Player 1
wins.

00:30:07.460 --> 00:30:11.576
Now the hard step I think in
proofs by induction is realizing

00:30:11.576 --> 00:30:15.473
that you're done.
So I claim we're now done,

00:30:15.473 --> 00:30:19.483
why are we done?
Well we know that it was pretty

00:30:19.483 --> 00:30:23.140
easy that all games of length 1
have a solution.

00:30:23.140 --> 00:30:27.103
That was pretty trivial.
And we've shown that if any

00:30:27.103 --> 00:30:32.617
game of length of N or fewer has
a solution, then games of N + 1

00:30:32.617 --> 00:30:35.420
have a solution.
So now let's see how we can

00:30:35.420 --> 00:30:38.049
proceed.
We know that games of length 1

00:30:38.049 --> 00:30:41.200
have a solution,
so let's consider games of

00:30:41.200 --> 00:30:43.215
length 2.
Games of length 2,

00:30:43.215 --> 00:30:45.570
do games of length 2 have a
solution?

00:30:45.570 --> 00:30:50.102
Well let's set N = 1.
We know that if games of length

00:30:50.102 --> 00:30:52.872
1 have a solution,
then any game of length 2 could

00:30:52.872 --> 00:30:56.660
be thought of as an initial step
followed by a game of length 1,

00:30:56.660 --> 00:30:59.367
but that has a solution,
so therefore games of length 2

00:30:59.367 --> 00:31:01.593
have a solution.
Now let's think of games with

00:31:01.593 --> 00:31:04.377
length 3, we've shown that games
with length 1 have a solution

00:31:04.377 --> 00:31:06.339
and games with length 2 have a
solution.

00:31:06.339 --> 00:31:09.475
Any game of length 3 can be
thought of as a game in which

00:31:09.475 --> 00:31:13.002
there's an initial step followed
by either a game of length 1 or

00:31:13.002 --> 00:31:16.359
a game of length 2,
each of which have a solution,

00:31:16.359 --> 00:31:20.430
so once again a game of length
3 has a solution and so on.

00:31:20.430 --> 00:31:23.699
So games of induction,
they work by building up on the

00:31:23.699 --> 00:31:26.536
length of the game,
and we're ending up knowing

00:31:26.536 --> 00:31:29.919
that we're done.
For those people who have never

00:31:29.919 --> 00:31:34.217
seen a proof by induction don't
worry I'm not going to test you

00:31:34.217 --> 00:31:37.059
on a proof with induction on the
exam,

00:31:37.059 --> 00:31:39.069
I just wanted you to see one
once.

00:31:39.069 --> 00:31:43.170
Let's all take a deep breath
and try and digest this a little

00:31:43.170 --> 00:31:48.661
bit by playing a game.
I'll leave it up there so you

00:31:48.661 --> 00:31:51.440
can stare at it.
We'll want it down again later.

00:31:57.549 --> 00:32:04.045
